This was my first time going to a Jollibee, and I'm not disappointed. I ordered the spaghetti with a 3 piece fried chicken dinner and got a mashed potato and gravy for a side. All of it was delicious in different ways. The spaghetti is no where near traditional, but that's what makes it so charming. The surprisingly sweet sauce with chopped hot dogs in it (yes, hot dogs)  reminded me of Campbell's Spaghetti-o with franks. Take with that what you will. The fried chicken was crispy, juicy, and flavorful. A little on the salty side, but not egregiously so. The mashed potatos were good; simple and filling.  Combine that with friendly staff, free wifi (I had to ask for the password though), and clean environment, this is an excellent restaurant.  I would come back here, and I'd recommend anyone to come here too.

Conveniently attached to Seafood City, this Jollibee impressed me, and was on-par if not better than Philippine locations.  We arrived just before the busy lunchtime rush, and ordered a variety of different meals ranging from chickenjoy (seasoned fried chicken) the Amazing Aloha (2 patties, bacon, honey mustard), and spaghetti.  The Aloha burger was on-point, and the chicken was irresistibly crispy and full of flavor.  The service was genuinely friendly as we were greeted with smiles and patience as we placed our long order. I must reiterate—the food tasted as good if not better than the Philippine locations!  They make an extra effort to keep this location spotless and clean, as we saw tables continually/thoroughly sanitized throughout our long stay (proximity to grocery Seafood Market)  Accessibility is also easy, as the parking is shared with Seafood City (actual parking lot) so no need to parallel park in an urban neighborhood. After your meal, you head straight to shopping, which is also a plus if you have lots of guests. I assume that most patrons do just that—make it a dining and shopping 1-2 combo.  Overall, I will be returning! Kudos to this location for making our stay happy!

We knew there was a Jollibee, and it wasn't far away, or so we thought.  Traffic was pretty rough to get here, going 20 miles in 55 minutes.  We arrived ravenous.  In a fit of starvation, we basically ordered one of everything on the menu.  Here are my thoughts from an entirely Caucasian perspective:  The hot dog comes with cheese, ketchup, and mayo on it. It's  very creamy and savory, and I dont think I could eat more than one.  The hamburger steak was pretty much what you would expect, a Salisbury steak in gravy with a side.  For people not familiar with Filipino food, their spaghetti has sugar and hot dogs in it.  It's good, but it's really sweet.  To my favorite part: Chicken Joy.  Get it.  Get a lot.  It's crispy and seasoned perfectly.  It's my favorite fast food chicken and it's over 700 miles away.  If one were in my area I would go pretty regularly.  All in all, I would like to visit here again, given the opportunity. Give it a try and see for yourself.
